<div id="content_text">

<br/>

<!-- inc publications_db -->

 <strong>November 5,  2013</strong><p><i>Forbes</i><p><strong>Five Steps to Conquering the Daily Email Deluge</strong><p><strong>By: JoAnne Yates</strong><br><p><P>
<I>Read the story below or view it on the
<A HREF="http://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesleadershipforum/2013/11/05/five-steps-to-conquering-the-daily-email-deluge/">Forbes</A> website.</I>



<p>
No matter what business we&rsquo;re in, most of us are swamped by emails, not to mention texts and instant messages. We&rsquo;re always fighting to stay afloat against the rising flood waters. Yet it often seems that the more messages we answer, or the faster we reply,&ndash; the worse it gets.</p> 
<p>I&rsquo;ve been analyzing email use since the 1980s. Our increased accessibility from technology was first seen as a tremendous advantage, but it&rsquo;s now a daily deluge. Through my research and the research of others, I&rsquo;ve found that there are some things we all can do to handle all those messages more efficiently.</p> 
<p><strong>1. Triage. </strong>The most important thing is triage. We&rsquo;ve all probably lost important emails because they simply scrolled off our screens as more emails arrived, becoming buried and forgotten. To prevent this from happening, categorize emails as they appear into at least three categories: &ldquo;low-hanging fruit,&rdquo; &ldquo;to do list,&rdquo; and &ldquo;very important.&rdquo; Try to deal with the low-hanging fruit messages immediately. They are the ones that can be quickly answered and removed from the in box. The ones for the &ldquo;to do&rdquo; list need a reply too, but they&rsquo;ll take more time and should be saved under that category. The very important messages should stay in your main in box so that every time you look at your screen you are reminded of those items. It&rsquo;s also helpful to flag those important messages as a high priority. The goal is never to leave work with emails scrolling off your screen. You should be able to see the contents of your inbox on a single screen.</p> 
<p><strong>2. Set limits for friends and colleagues. </strong>Individual policies are best combined with agreements among friends, family, and colleagues on communication norms. &nbsp;Working with communication partners to set limits is especially important for texts and instant messages, which are generally more intrusive, because we often feel the need to respond right away. Negotiate with friends and family about the times when you won&rsquo;t text, or you may easily spend 30 minutes &ldquo;discussing&rdquo; a noncritical topic in the middle of the workday. If they need to send messages during those times, encourage them to use email, and then file those messages using the triage system described above.</p> 
<p><strong>3. Turn off alerts. </strong>As you work with friends and family to set agreed on limits, also set limits for yourself. Disable the sounds and visual notification windows that alert you to new messages. When you hear a ping or see an email notification, it&rsquo;s natural to want to read that text or email right away. But if you don&rsquo;t know it has arrived, you&rsquo;re more likely to stay focused on other work. And if that other work requires concentration, like putting together a presentation, set aside an hour or whatever you need to accomplish it before checking messages. There&rsquo;s a lot of research out there on multitasking, and it shows that people can&rsquo;t actually do two things at once. Every time you go back and forth between tasks, you have to reorient yourself, and that wastes time, which eventually adds up. Instead, turn off the sound and visual alerts and take control of when you check your messages.</p> 
<p><strong>4. Check personal mailboxes less often. </strong>If you have a separate personal email address, set specific times to check those messages. You might look at them before work, at lunch and when you leave the office. Unless there is something specific you are waiting for, you shouldn&rsquo;t be monitoring this all day.</p> 
<p><strong>5. Shut down at night. </strong>This brings up the issue of how often you should monitor work email outside of the workday. In my research with Wanda Orlikowski and <STRONG>Melissa Mazmanian</STRONG>, we&rsquo;ve found an escalating dynamic in that the more you make yourself available, the more people assume you&rsquo;ll be available. You may think you&rsquo;re just replying to an email or two late at night, but communication via any technology is social and collective. You&rsquo;re interacting with other people who are forming expectations about your availability, and you&rsquo;re forming expectations about their availability. Once you accept the fact that communication activity is social, then you have to come up with collective ways to manage it, which means setting expectations. For example, let coworkers know that you&rsquo;ll check your email no later than a certain time each evening and then not again until the morning. If you start replying to emails at 2 a.m., you&rsquo;ll set the expectation that you&rsquo;re available around the clock. Establish your norms, let others know those norms, and then stick to them. Encourage coworkers to do the same.</p> 
<p>A lot of these tips involve self control, as well as agreements on collective norms. We contribute a lot to the daily deluge with our constant desire to check messages and immediately reply. If we train ourselves to triage messages and work with our communication partners to set limits and establish norms, then we can better manage the entire process. Eventually, it won&rsquo;t be so overwhelming, and we become a lot more efficient. The most important thing is to control your technology. Don&rsquo;t let it control you.</p> 



<br><TITLE>Five Steps to Conquering the Daily Email Deluge</TITLE>

</div>
</blockquote>
